metadata.name: Appropriate Hidden Breeze #133
metadata.description:
"Appropriate Hidden Breeze" is a study of blending gradients on a grid. 

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size 12x12" @ 300 DPI

metadata.name: a fleeting moment #183
metadata.description:
Abstract expressionism always has been, and always will be, my first love. With this piece, the initial premise was "can I write a bit of code that will render images in the style that I actually paint in real life?" 

It took several full days of poking and prodding, and I departed from the original mission once I had what I was looking for, but in general, I think I succeeded. My wife was looking over my shoulder at one point, and thought I was looking at a scan of one of my actual paintings, which sounds like success to me. 

Created with love in p5.js

metadata.name: Pulsar #38
metadata.description:
When exploring new possibilities for a new work, I stumbled across an article on Pulsar map. Created by astronomer Frank Drake and Carl Sagan, this map serves as a galactic address of our solar system for any extra-terrestrial civilization to find using pulsars as signposts. Though chances of any kind of life form intercepting the map are slim, I'm still fascinated both by the possibility of another planetary civilization finding the map (and by extension our Earth), and the thought of using pulsar -- the remaining corpse of ancient massive star -- as universal signposts and landmarks to map the Earth position for any kind of possible civilization. To me there's something so poetic about this; it made me thinks of how small are we, the Humans, compared to those rotating pulsars that we use as mere landmarks to our location...let alone the whole universe. We are just floating stardust after all.

In this piece I use Lissajous curve array with randomized variable to position the stars and generate spline as 'star trails'. The Lissajous array is interpolated with Perlin noise array to make it less smooth and looks more random.



----------
Control:
Press [s] to capture a screenshot of the current viewport.
Press [t] to toggle the star trails (default: enabled).



Made with Cables.gl

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: GEN XYZ Das Occult #7490
metadata.description:
A 10k Generative Profile Pic collection
GEN XYZ Das Occult - by culla - @tamccullough

move over cryptopunks
there is a new group on the scene

100% code - not an image composition

A bunch of common palettes
A selection of rare palettes
And a smaller set of ultra rare palettes
However, rarity will be based on what combinations the code produces

The majority of tokens will not have a special trait
However your token might have one or even multiple special traits
But, be aware that only the last special trait added will be listed in the features

Even then, look closely, because not all aspects of the canvas are included in the features. Collectors should still look closely and choose what they like when buying on secondary.

Which team are you on? X or O?

follow culla on twitter for updates. Or maybe __acolyte__

If the non reserved tokens mint out quickly, Access List mints will have 24 hours to mint reserves assigned to those wallets

Thank you for supporting an emerging artist in the generative art space

Access List reserves were given to holders of the following PFP collections created by culla
2x for each Basqunk held
1x for each Inkspunk, TwoFourQunk, V0iD, DeeManz, Punkasso and CR0$$KULL
You would have needed to transfer the above tokens to your mint wallet at the time of the snapshot

share your tokens on social media with #genxyznft
Made with love by culla using p5.js

metadata.name: Bound #104
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten – it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself – the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold – new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we’ve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.

---

Press ‘1’-’9’ to increase resolution
Press 's' to save an image of the output at the current resolution

Created with p5.js
For third party license information, please see license.md

---

TENDER x David Brice Allen
July 2022
